<!-- ABOUT COLD WAVES -->
<article class="content-card">
  <h2>About Cold Waves</h2>
  <p>
    A cold wave is a weather event characterized by a sudden drop in temperature that can lead to frostbite,
    hypothermia, and severe health risks. Northern India, including Punjab, Haryana, Rajasthan, and Delhi,
    frequently experience cold waves during the winter months.
  </p>
  <p>
    Cold waves affect vulnerable groups the most: elderly people, children, homeless populations, and outdoor workers.
  </p>
</article>

<!-- PREPAREDNESS -->
<article class="content-card">
  <h2>Preparedness Before a Cold Wave</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Wear multiple layers of warm clothing.</li>
    <li>Keep your home insulated and block cold air leaks.</li>
    <li>Store warm blankets, gloves, caps, and socks.</li>
    <li>Ensure the elderly and infants stay warm.</li>
    <li>Keep emergency numbers handy in case of frostbite or hypothermia.</li>
    <li>Avoid using open flame heaters inside closed rooms.</li>
  </ul>
</article>

<!-- DOs & DON'Ts -->
<article class="content-card">
  <h2>Do‚Äôs & Don‚Äôts During Cold Waves</h2>

  <h3>‚úî Do‚Äôs</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Wear thermal layers and woolen clothing.</li>
    <li>Drink warm water regularly.</li>
    <li>Use safe heating devices.</li>
    <li>Check on neighbors, especially elderly people.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>‚ùå Don‚Äôts</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Do NOT use coal or wood burners indoors ‚Äî risk of suffocation.</li>
    <li>Do NOT leave infants or pets exposed to cold air.</li>
    <li>Do NOT drive in early morning fog without proper visibility.</li>
    <li>Do NOT consume alcohol ‚Äî it reduces body warmth.</li>
  </ul>
</article>

